WEBVTT

0
00:00:00.090 --> 00:00:00.370
You know,

1
00:00:00.529 --> 00:00:01.809
as a senior analyst,

2
00:00:01.889 --> 00:00:04.210
I see hundreds of business plans.

3
00:00:04.409 --> 00:00:06.599
They all cross my desk every single year.

4
00:00:06.809 --> 00:00:07.570
And let me tell you,

5
00:00:07.969 --> 00:00:08.829
everyone is passionate.

6
00:00:09.050 --> 00:00:10.689
Everyone thinks they've got the next big thing,

7
00:00:10.810 --> 00:00:11.890
but here's the hard truth,

8
00:00:12.170 --> 00:00:13.079
most new ideas,

9
00:00:13.289 --> 00:00:14.869
they're just destined to fail.

10
00:00:15.329 --> 00:00:15.680
I mean,

11
00:00:15.850 --> 00:00:16.530
check this out,

12
00:00:16.729 --> 00:00:21.760
studies show a staggering 80% of new products fail in their very first year.

13
00:00:22.170 --> 00:00:23.750
That's just a brutal reality,

14
00:00:23.850 --> 00:00:24.170
right?

15
00:00:24.590 --> 00:00:24.969
So,

16
00:00:25.069 --> 00:00:27.829
my job isn't really about finding the good ideas,

17
00:00:28.030 --> 00:00:30.170
it's about filtering out all the bad ones,

18
00:00:30.350 --> 00:00:31.250
ruthlessly,

19
00:00:31.549 --> 00:00:33.669
before they drain valuable time and resources.

20
00:00:34.450 --> 00:00:36.889
So how do the successful companies do it?

21
00:00:37.130 --> 00:00:39.369
How do they separate the winners from the,

22
00:00:39.490 --> 00:00:39.729
well,

23
00:00:39.889 --> 00:00:41.430
the disasters waiting to happen?

24
00:00:41.729 --> 00:00:44.229
The answer is a really solid screening process.

25
00:00:44.450 --> 00:00:45.869
Think of it like a gatekeeper,

26
00:00:46.090 --> 00:00:50.110
with a series of checkpoints that only the most promising ideas get through.

27
00:00:50.209 --> 00:00:51.150
It's not magic,

28
00:00:51.290 --> 00:00:51.950
it's a method.

29
00:00:52.549 --> 00:00:52.930
So,

30
00:00:52.990 --> 00:00:53.330
OK,

31
00:00:53.430 --> 00:00:54.599
let's pull back the curtain

32
00:00:54.709 --> 00:00:56.790
and I'll show you exactly how it's done.

33
00:00:57.189 --> 00:00:57.349
All right,

34
00:00:57.470 --> 00:01:00.569
so before we even think about committing serious resources,

35
00:01:00.750 --> 00:01:04.019
every single idea has to go through a high-level triage.

36
00:01:04.269 --> 00:01:07.610
We use this simple but honestly incredibly powerful tool.

37
00:01:07.709 --> 00:01:09.959
It's called the Real Win Worth It screen,

38
00:01:10.269 --> 00:01:13.050
and it is the absolute first line of defense against,

39
00:01:13.190 --> 00:01:13.540
well,

40
00:01:13.830 --> 00:01:14.849
against wishful thinking.

41
00:01:15.349 --> 00:01:15.589
First,

42
00:01:15.730 --> 00:01:17.569
Is the market real?

43
00:01:17.650 --> 00:01:19.269
And we have to be brutally honest here.

44
00:01:19.410 --> 00:01:21.839
Is there a genuine need for this?

45
00:01:22.050 --> 00:01:23.410
We're not just talking about market size,

46
00:01:23.489 --> 00:01:24.279
so that's important.

47
00:01:24.449 --> 00:01:27.129
We're talking about the intensity of the customer's need.

48
00:01:27.370 --> 00:01:31.849
Are you solving a mild inconvenience or a massive hair on fire pain point?

49
00:01:32.129 --> 00:01:32.290
You know,

50
00:01:32.330 --> 00:01:34.449
an app for left-handed musicians might sound cool,

51
00:01:34.709 --> 00:01:36.330
but if that market is just too tiny,

52
00:01:36.410 --> 00:01:39.110
it's not real enough to justify a big investment.

53
00:01:39.569 --> 00:01:39.919
OK,

54
00:01:40.169 --> 00:01:40.839
next question.

55
00:01:41.089 --> 00:01:42.330
Can we actually win?

56
00:01:42.669 --> 00:01:43.010
Look,

57
00:01:43.190 --> 00:01:45.669
it's not enough to have a great product in a big market.

58
00:01:45.949 --> 00:01:47.529
You have to look in the mirror and ask,

59
00:01:47.790 --> 00:01:49.620
do we have what it takes?

60
00:01:49.830 --> 00:01:50.750
Do we have the tech,

61
00:01:50.889 --> 00:01:51.459
the team,

62
00:01:51.629 --> 00:01:53.830
the brand to actually dominate?

63
00:01:54.110 --> 00:01:56.610
This is where we really dig into the competitive landscape.

64
00:01:56.750 --> 00:02:00.739
Is it a total bloodbath out there or is there actually room for us to play?

65
00:02:01.029 --> 00:02:03.349
Are there big barriers to entry that will protect us,

66
00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:06.069
or could a dozen new competitors just pop up overnight?

67
00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:07.269
And finally,

68
00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:08.119
the big one,

69
00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:09.630
is the venture worth it?

70
00:02:09.750 --> 00:02:10.899
We're talking bottom line here.

71
00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:12.899
Is this thing actually gonna be profitable

72
00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:14.759
and at a risk level we can stomach?

73
00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:17.419
But just as important is the strategic question,

74
00:02:17.559 --> 00:02:19.429
does this even make sense for our business?

75
00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:19.759
I mean,

76
00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:21.559
a project could be profitable on paper,

77
00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:23.729
but if it drags us away from our core mission,

78
00:02:23.889 --> 00:02:25.919
or just ends up cannibalizing our other products,

79
00:02:26.039 --> 00:02:26.350
you know,

80
00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:29.639
stealing sales from our bestsellers without actually growing the pie,

81
00:02:29.869 --> 00:02:30.830
then it's just not worth it.

82
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:31.679
Simple as that.

83
00:02:32.490 --> 00:02:36.360
So if an idea makes it through that first real win worth it screen,

84
00:02:36.559 --> 00:02:37.440
congratulations,

85
00:02:37.679 --> 00:02:39.860
but that's when the real work begins.

86
00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:41.360
Now it's time for a much,

87
00:02:41.559 --> 00:02:43.039
much deeper analysis.

88
00:02:43.279 --> 00:02:46.020
I like to break this down into 3 fundamental pillars.

89
00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:49.839
This is where we go from a quick reality check to a full blown investigation.

90
00:02:50.279 --> 00:02:51.399
So what are these pillars?

91
00:02:51.649 --> 00:02:51.809
Well,

92
00:02:51.910 --> 00:02:52.309
first,

93
00:02:52.369 --> 00:02:53.919
there are the market factors.

94
00:02:54.130 --> 00:02:55.429
Here we get really rigorous,

95
00:02:55.490 --> 00:02:57.550
assessing the entire industry structure.

96
00:02:57.809 --> 00:03:00.910
We're looking at things like the bargaining power of your customers and suppliers,

97
00:03:01.020 --> 00:03:01.690
and crucially,

98
00:03:01.850 --> 00:03:03.410
the threat of substitute products that could

99
00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:05.720
just make your great idea obsolete overnight.

100
00:03:06.089 --> 00:03:06.470
Second,

101
00:03:06.649 --> 00:03:08.520
we have product and technical factors.

102
00:03:08.729 --> 00:03:09.809
The big question here is,

103
00:03:09.929 --> 00:03:12.800
can we actually build this thing to a high standard and more importantly,

104
00:03:12.929 --> 00:03:13.919
can we scale it?

105
00:03:14.169 --> 00:03:14.690
And third,

106
00:03:14.809 --> 00:03:15.960
the financial factors,

107
00:03:16.169 --> 00:03:16.490
you know,

108
00:03:16.649 --> 00:03:17.639
the brass tacks.

109
00:03:17.809 --> 00:03:19.529
What's the potential return on investment?

110
00:03:19.949 --> 00:03:20.660
The thing is,

111
00:03:20.830 --> 00:03:22.789
each one of these pillars has to be solid,

112
00:03:22.830 --> 00:03:24.750
or the whole idea just falls apart.

113
00:03:25.149 --> 00:03:25.309
Now,

114
00:03:25.429 --> 00:03:27.039
here's a crucial layer to all this,

115
00:03:27.309 --> 00:03:28.130
context.

116
00:03:28.550 --> 00:03:31.820
We don't just weigh these pillars the same way for every single idea.

117
00:03:32.029 --> 00:03:32.500
Nope.

118
00:03:32.789 --> 00:03:34.869
How much weight we give them depends entirely on

119
00:03:34.869 --> 00:03:36.820
where the industry is in its life cycle.

120
00:03:37.059 --> 00:03:37.690
Think about it.

121
00:03:37.830 --> 00:03:39.570
In a high-risk pioneering stage,

122
00:03:39.789 --> 00:03:40.669
you've got new tech,

123
00:03:40.869 --> 00:03:41.869
tons of competition,

124
00:03:42.070 --> 00:03:44.289
the threat of new companies jumping in is massive.

125
00:03:44.554 --> 00:03:45.994
So we're laser focused on,

126
00:03:46.115 --> 00:03:48.505
can we build it and can we build a moat around it.

127
00:03:48.755 --> 00:03:50.654
But if you're in a stable maturity stage,

128
00:03:50.835 --> 00:03:52.164
the game totally changes.

129
00:03:52.315 --> 00:03:53.914
It's all about intense rivalry,

130
00:03:54.115 --> 00:03:55.195
defending your market share,

131
00:03:55.235 --> 00:03:57.345
and making your costs as low as possible.

132
00:03:57.585 --> 00:04:00.494
Your strategy absolutely has to fit the stage you're in.

133
00:04:00.895 --> 00:04:01.115
OK,

134
00:04:01.235 --> 00:04:03.104
so we've got this deep dive framework,

135
00:04:03.315 --> 00:04:04.585
but how do we make it efficient?

136
00:04:04.835 --> 00:04:07.294
We can't spend 6 months on every idea.

137
00:04:07.779 --> 00:04:08.100
Well,

138
00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:10.050
we apply a two-tier filter.

139
00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:13.529
This is all about separating the absolute non-negotiables,

140
00:04:13.740 --> 00:04:14.660
the must-haves,

141
00:04:14.820 --> 00:04:15.809
from the nice to haves.

142
00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:18.298
This is really how we avoid wasting a ton of

143
00:04:18.298 --> 00:04:21.320
time analyzing an idea that's already dead on arrival.

144
00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:22.179
So,

145
00:04:22.380 --> 00:04:23.440
the must-haves,

146
00:04:23.660 --> 00:04:25.450
these are your knockout questions.

147
00:04:25.700 --> 00:04:27.250
Think of them like hard gates.

148
00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:29.529
Does the idea fit our core strategy?

149
00:04:29.779 --> 00:04:30.109
Is it,

150
00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:30.540
you know,

151
00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:31.170
legal?

152
00:04:31.420 --> 00:04:33.899
Can we actually build it with today's technology?

153
00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:36.119
If you get a no on any one of these,

154
00:04:36.290 --> 00:04:36.799
that's it.

155
00:04:36.970 --> 00:04:37.929
Project is dead,

156
00:04:38.130 --> 00:04:38.880
it's over.

157
00:04:39.170 --> 00:04:41.690
Only the ideas that get a yes on every single one

158
00:04:41.690 --> 00:04:43.589
of these gates get to move on to the next round,

159
00:04:43.850 --> 00:04:45.679
where we score them against the wood likes.

160
00:04:46.049 --> 00:04:48.769
And that brings us to the quantitative climax,

161
00:04:48.809 --> 00:04:49.510
if you will.

162
00:04:49.850 --> 00:04:53.429
This is where we actually assign a score to the ideas that survived,

163
00:04:53.570 --> 00:04:55.149
to figure out their final ranking.

164
00:04:55.410 --> 00:04:58.890
We're moving away from the gut checks and into a much more objective,

165
00:04:59.049 --> 00:05:00.369
data-driven comparison.

166
00:05:00.989 --> 00:05:03.589
So here's how that scoring actually works in practice.

167
00:05:03.790 --> 00:05:05.369
We use what's called a weighted model.

168
00:05:05.709 --> 00:05:05.950
First,

169
00:05:06.049 --> 00:05:08.730
we assign a weight to each of our wood-like criteria,

170
00:05:08.869 --> 00:05:11.130
based on how important it is to our strategy.

171
00:05:11.470 --> 00:05:11.589
So,

172
00:05:11.670 --> 00:05:12.149
for example,

173
00:05:12.279 --> 00:05:14.929
market size and competitive edge might be really important,

174
00:05:15.230 --> 00:05:16.660
so they get a heavy weight of 5.

175
00:05:16.989 --> 00:05:18.149
Then we score the idea,

176
00:05:18.269 --> 00:05:19.529
say from 1 to 10,

177
00:05:19.670 --> 00:05:21.859
on how well it performs on each of those things.

178
00:05:22.109 --> 00:05:23.709
You just multiply the weight by the score,

179
00:05:23.859 --> 00:05:24.470
add it all up,

180
00:05:24.589 --> 00:05:25.070
and boom,

181
00:05:25.190 --> 00:05:26.609
you've got an initial project score.

182
00:05:26.709 --> 00:05:27.170
In this case,

183
00:05:27.269 --> 00:05:28.290
it's 125.

184
00:05:28.920 --> 00:05:29.829
But wait a minute,

185
00:05:30.049 --> 00:05:31.320
that initial score,

186
00:05:31.529 --> 00:05:33.029
that's just the tip of the iceberg.

187
00:05:33.170 --> 00:05:35.109
It's only telling you about the opportunity,

188
00:05:35.290 --> 00:05:36.470
the shiny upside.

189
00:05:36.769 --> 00:05:39.290
What it completely ignores are all the threats

190
00:05:39.290 --> 00:05:41.869
and risks lurking just below the surface.

191
00:05:42.049 --> 00:05:42.850
And let me tell you,

192
00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:48.269
a project with a high score and massive risk is a trap you do not want to fall into.

193
00:05:48.809 --> 00:05:49.040
So,

194
00:05:49.209 --> 00:05:51.010
to get a truly realistic picture,

195
00:05:51.130 --> 00:05:52.589
we have to identify and then

196
00:05:52.839 --> 00:05:55.890
quantify the major risk factors as negative points.

197
00:05:56.220 --> 00:05:58.380
Is the technology totally unproven?

198
00:05:58.459 --> 00:05:58.739
OK,

199
00:05:58.859 --> 00:06:00.200
that's -15 points.

200
00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:02.380
Is there a high chance your competitors are going

201
00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:04.600
to start a price war the second you launch?

202
00:06:04.899 --> 00:06:06.440
That could be a -20.

203
00:06:06.779 --> 00:06:09.420
We subtract all of these from that initial score to

204
00:06:09.420 --> 00:06:12.920
get a final and frankly more sober risk-adjusted score.

205
00:06:13.140 --> 00:06:14.739
That's the number that really matters.

206
00:06:15.489 --> 00:06:18.690
But even with a fantastic risk-adjusted score,

207
00:06:18.859 --> 00:06:20.730
we're still not quite done.

208
00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:22.279
There is one last,

209
00:06:22.299 --> 00:06:25.260
absolutely vital question that an analyst has to

210
00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:27.369
ask before they give the final green light,

211
00:06:27.540 --> 00:06:28.209
and honestly,

212
00:06:28.380 --> 00:06:32.200
this is the step that separates the good analysts from the truly great ones.

213
00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:33.959
And it's all about this,

214
00:06:34.059 --> 00:06:35.600
strategic alignment.

215
00:06:35.820 --> 00:06:38.500
It's about looking past the numbers on the spreadsheet and really

216
00:06:38.500 --> 00:06:41.339
seeing how this new venture fits into the company's bigger picture.

217
00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:43.850
A project can have an amazing score,

218
00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:46.029
but if it doesn't actually enhance our brand,

219
00:06:46.250 --> 00:06:49.369
or use our core skills or line up with our long-term mission,

220
00:06:49.690 --> 00:06:50.850
it might just be a very,

221
00:06:50.970 --> 00:06:52.480
very profitable distraction.

222
00:06:52.850 --> 00:06:55.109
And that right there is the final takeaway.

223
00:06:55.410 --> 00:06:57.549
A project can't just be profitable today,

224
00:06:57.640 --> 00:06:59.519
it has to be relevant for where the company,

225
00:06:59.690 --> 00:07:00.140
the market,

226
00:07:00.209 --> 00:07:00.640
and yeah,

227
00:07:01.010 --> 00:07:02.750
the whole world is headed tomorrow.

228
00:07:03.170 --> 00:07:03.359
So,

229
00:07:03.369 --> 00:07:05.989
the ultimate question isn't just can this idea win,

230
00:07:06.209 --> 00:07:09.230
it's will this idea help us keep winning for years to come.

231
00:07:09.579 --> 00:07:11.339
And that's the kind of thinking that turns a

232
00:07:11.339 --> 00:07:13.959
pretty good idea into a massive lasting success.